"You can extract the surface of nearly any object within ``pyvista`` using "
"the :meth:`~pyvista.DataObjectFilters.extract_surface` filter."
msgstr ""

#: ../../pyvista/doc/source/examples/01-filter/extract_surface.rst:48
msgid "Surface extraction of nonlinear cells"
msgstr ""

#: ../../pyvista/doc/source/examples/01-filter/extract_surface.rst:49
msgid ""
"Here we create a single :attr:`~pyvista.CellType.QUADRATIC_HEXAHEDRON` cell "
"and then extract its surface to demonstrate how to extract the surface of an"
" :class:`~pyvista.UnstructuredGrid`. First define points of a linear cell:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../pyvista/doc/source/examples/01-filter/extract_surface.rst:81
msgid ""
"Next, define the \"midside\" points of a quad cell. See the definition of a "
":vtk:`vtkQuadraticHexahedron`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../pyvista/doc/source/examples/01-filter/extract_surface.rst:115
msgid ""
"We introduce a minor variation to the location of the mid-side points seed "
"the random numbers for reproducibility"
msgstr ""

#: ../../pyvista/doc/source/examples/01-filter/extract_surface.rst:154
msgid ""
"Finally, extract the surface and plot it. Note that the `'dataset_surface'` "
"algorithm is necessary to use when generating surfaces from non-linear "
"cells. Setting ``algorithm=None`` also works."
msgstr ""

#: ../../pyvista/doc/source/examples/01-filter/extract_surface.rst:202
msgid "Nonlinear Surface Subdivision"
msgstr ""

#: ../../pyvista/doc/source/examples/01-filter/extract_surface.rst:203
msgid ""
"Should your UnstructuredGrid contain quadratic cells, you can generate a "
"smooth surface based on the position of the \"mid-edge\" nodes.  This allows"
" the plotting of cells containing curvature.  For additional reference, "
"please see: https://prod.sandia.gov/techlib-noauth/access-"
"control.cgi/2004/041617.pdf"
msgstr ""

#: ../../pyvista/doc/source/examples/01-filter/extract_surface.rst:258
msgid "Compare Surface Extraction Algorithms"
msgstr ""

#: ../../pyvista/doc/source/examples/01-filter/extract_surface.rst:259
msgid ""
"The filter :meth:`~pyvista.DataObjectFilters.extract_surface` provides the "
"option to select which internal VTK algorithm to use for surface extraction:"
" :vtk:`vtkGeometryFilter` or :vtk:`vtkDataSetSurfaceFilter`. Both algorithms"
" produce similar surfaces, but they differ in important ways. As the "
"following examples will demonstrate, it is generally preferable to use the "
"geometry algorithm."
msgstr ""

#: ../../pyvista/doc/source/examples/01-filter/extract_surface.rst:266
msgid "Structural Preservation"
msgstr ""

#: ../../pyvista/doc/source/examples/01-filter/extract_surface.rst:267
msgid ""
"The geometry algorithm preserves structure when converting between mesh "
"types, whereas the dataset surface algorithm does not."
msgstr ""

#: ../../pyvista/doc/source/examples/01-filter/extract_surface.rst:270
msgid ""
"For example, let's create a simple :class:`~pyvista.PolyData` mesh using "
":meth:`~pyvista.Cone` and cast it to :class:`~pyvista.UnstructuredGrid`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../pyvista/doc/source/examples/01-filter/extract_surface.rst:290
msgid ""
"If we convert it back to a surface, the geometry algorithm returns the "
"original surface with the same order of points and the same cell "
"connectivity arrays."
msgstr ""

#: ../../pyvista/doc/source/examples/01-filter/extract_surface.rst:312
msgid "But the dataset surface algorithm does not."
msgstr ""

#: ../../pyvista/doc/source/examples/01-filter/extract_surface.rst:333
msgid "Compare the point ids of the original mesh to the generated surfaces."
msgstr ""

#: ../../pyvista/doc/source/examples/01-filter/extract_surface.rst:396
msgid "Closed Surface Generation"
msgstr ""

#: ../../pyvista/doc/source/examples/01-filter/extract_surface.rst:397
msgid ""
"The geometry algorithm generates closed surfaces in cases where a closed "
"surface is expected, whereas the dataset surface algorithm may not. For "
"example, extract the surface of :class:`~pyvista.ImageData` comprised of a "
"single :attr:`~pyvista.CellType.VOXEL` cell."
msgstr ""

#: ../../pyvista/doc/source/examples/01-filter/extract_surface.rst:421
msgid ""
"Both algorithms convert the single 3D cell into a cube with six 2D "
":attr:`~pyvista.CellType.QUAD` faces."
msgstr ""

#: ../../pyvista/doc/source/examples/01-filter/extract_surface.rst:448
msgid ""
"However, the geometry algorithm returns a closed surface with eight points "
"and no open edges."
msgstr ""

#: ../../pyvista/doc/source/examples/01-filter/extract_surface.rst:467
msgid ""
"In contrast, the dataset surface algorithm returns a surface with duplicate "
"points and many open edges."
msgstr ""

#: ../../pyvista/doc/source/examples/01-filter/extract_surface.rst:486
msgid ""
"This can be fixed with a call to :meth:`~pyvista.PolyDataFilters.clean`, "
"however."
msgstr ""

#: ../../pyvista/doc/source/examples/01-filter/extract_surface.rst:506
msgid ""
"Note that a closed surface is important for some calculations. E.g. the "
"filter :meth:`~pyvista.DataSetFilters.select_interior_points` requires a "
"closed surface by default, and properties like "
":attr:`~pyvista.PolyData.volume` assume the input is a closed surface."
msgstr ""

