#: ../../pyvista/doc/source/examples/01-filter/image_representations.rst:24
msgid "Image Data Representations"
msgstr ""

#: ../../pyvista/doc/source/examples/01-filter/image_representations.rst:25
msgid ""
"This example demonstrates how to use "
":meth:`~pyvista.ImageDataFilters.points_to_cells` and "
":meth:`~pyvista.ImageDataFilters.cells_to_points` to re-mesh "
":class:`~pyvista.ImageData`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../pyvista/doc/source/examples/01-filter/image_representations.rst:29
msgid ""
"These filters can be used to ensure that image data has an appropriate "
"representation when generating plots and/or when using either point- or "
"cell-based filters such as :meth:`ImageDataFilters.image_threshold "
"<pyvista.ImageDataFilters.image_threshold>` (point-based) and "
":meth:`DataSetFilters.threshold <pyvista.DataSetFilters.threshold>` (cell-"
"based)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../pyvista/doc/source/examples/01-filter/image_representations.rst:38
msgid "Representations of 3D Volumes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../pyvista/doc/source/examples/01-filter/image_representations.rst:39
msgid ""
"Create image data of a 3D volume with eight points and a discrete scalar "
"data array."
msgstr ""

#: ../../pyvista/doc/source/examples/01-filter/image_representations.rst:64
msgid ""
"If we plot the volume, it is represented as a single cell with eight points,"
" and the point data is interpolated to color the cell."
msgstr ""

#: ../../pyvista/doc/source/examples/01-filter/image_representations.rst:110
msgid ""
"However, in many applications (e.g. 3D medical imaging), the scalar data "
"arrays represent discretized samples at the centers of voxels. As such, it "
"may be more appropriate to represent the data as eight voxel cells instead "
"of eight points. We can use "
":meth:`~pyvista.ImageDataFilters.points_to_cells` to generate a cell-based "
"representation."
msgstr ""

#: ../../pyvista/doc/source/examples/01-filter/image_representations.rst:132
msgid ""
"Now, when we plot the volume, we have a more appropriate representation with"
" eight voxel cells and the scalar data is no longer interpolated."
msgstr ""

#: ../../pyvista/doc/source/examples/01-filter/image_representations.rst:178
#: ../../pyvista/doc/source/examples/01-filter/image_representations.rst:737
msgid "Let's plot the two representations together for comparison."
msgstr ""

#: ../../pyvista/doc/source/examples/01-filter/image_representations.rst:180
msgid ""
"For visualization, we color the points volume (inner mesh) and only show the"
" edges of the cells volume (outer mesh). We also plot the cell centers in "
"red. Note how the centers of the image of the cells correspond to the points"
" of the points image."
msgstr ""

#: ../../pyvista/doc/source/examples/01-filter/image_representations.rst:241
msgid ""
"As long as only one kind of scalar data is used (i.e. either point or cell "
"data, but not both), it is possible to move between representations without "
"loss of data."
msgstr ""

#: ../../pyvista/doc/source/examples/01-filter/image_representations.rst:270
msgid "Point Filters with Image Data"
msgstr ""

#: ../../pyvista/doc/source/examples/01-filter/image_representations.rst:271
msgid ""
"Use a point representation of the image when working with point-based "
"filters such as :meth:`~pyvista.ImageDataFilters.image_threshold`. If the "
"image only has cell data, use "
":meth:`~pyvista.ImageDataFilters.cells_to_points` re-mesh the input first. "
"Here, we reuse the point-based image defined earlier."
msgstr ""

#: ../../pyvista/doc/source/examples/01-filter/image_representations.rst:276
#: ../../pyvista/doc/source/examples/01-filter/image_representations.rst:433
msgid "For context, we first show the input data array."
msgstr ""

#: ../../pyvista/doc/source/examples/01-filter/image_representations.rst:300
#: ../../pyvista/doc/source/examples/01-filter/image_representations.rst:457
msgid "Now apply the filter and print the result."
msgstr ""

#: ../../pyvista/doc/source/examples/01-filter/image_representations.rst:325
msgid ""
"The filter returns binary point data as expected. Values equal to or greater"
" or than the threshold of ``2`` are ones and less than the threshold are "
"zeros."
msgstr ""

#: ../../pyvista/doc/source/examples/01-filter/image_representations.rst:328
msgid ""
"However, in plotting it, the point values are linearly interpolated. For "
"visualizing binary data, this interpolation is not desirable."
msgstr ""

#: ../../pyvista/doc/source/examples/01-filter/image_representations.rst:374
msgid ""
"To better visualize the result, convert the image of the point returned by "
"the filter to a cell representation with "
":meth:`~pyvista.ImageDataFilters.points_to_cells` before plotting."
msgstr ""

#: ../../pyvista/doc/source/examples/01-filter/image_representations.rst:422
msgid "The binary data is now correctly visualized as binary data."
msgstr ""

#: ../../pyvista/doc/source/examples/01-filter/image_representations.rst:427
msgid "Cell Filters with Image Data"
msgstr ""

#: ../../pyvista/doc/source/examples/01-filter/image_representations.rst:428
msgid ""
"Use a cell representation of the image when working with cell-based filters "
"such as :meth:`~pyvista.DataSetFilters.threshold`. If the image only has "
"point data, use :meth:`~pyvista.ImageDataFilters.points_to_cells` to re-mesh"
" the input first. Here, we reuse the cell-based image created earlier."
msgstr ""

#: ../../pyvista/doc/source/examples/01-filter/image_representations.rst:482
msgid ""
"When the input is cell data, this filter returns seven discrete values "
"greater than or equal to the threshold value of ``2`` as expected."
msgstr ""

#: ../../pyvista/doc/source/examples/01-filter/image_representations.rst:485
msgid ""
"If we plot the result, the cells also produce the correct visualization."
msgstr ""

#: ../../pyvista/doc/source/examples/01-filter/image_representations.rst:530
msgid ""
"However, if we apply the same filter to a point-based representation of the "
"image, the filter does not produce the desired result."
msgstr ""

#: ../../pyvista/doc/source/examples/01-filter/image_representations.rst:556
msgid ""
"In this case, since the image of the point only has a single cell, the "
"filter has no effect on the data array's values. The thresholded values are "
"the same as the input values."
msgstr ""

#: ../../pyvista/doc/source/examples/01-filter/image_representations.rst:560
msgid ""
"Plotting the result confirms this. The plot is identical to the initial plot"
" of the point-based image shown at the beginning of this example."
msgstr ""

#: ../../pyvista/doc/source/examples/01-filter/image_representations.rst:607
msgid "Representations of 2D Images"
msgstr ""

#: ../../pyvista/doc/source/examples/01-filter/image_representations.rst:608
msgid ""
"The filters :meth:`~pyvista.ImageDataFilters.points_to_cells` and "
":meth:`~pyvista.ImageDataFilters.cells_to_points` can similarly be used with"
" 2D images."
msgstr ""

#: ../../pyvista/doc/source/examples/01-filter/image_representations.rst:612
msgid ""
"For this example, we create a 4x4 2D grayscale image with 16 points to "
"represent 16 pixels."
msgstr ""

#: ../../pyvista/doc/source/examples/01-filter/image_representations.rst:633
msgid ""
"Plot the image. As before, the plot does not appear correct since the point "
"data is interpolated, and nine cells are shown rather than the desired 16 "
"(one for each pixel)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../pyvista/doc/source/examples/01-filter/image_representations.rst:688
msgid ""
"To visualize the image correctly, we first use "
":meth:`~pyvista.ImageDataFilters.points_to_cells` to get a cell-based "
"representation of the image and plot the result. The plot now correctly "
"shows 16-pixel cells with discrete values."
msgstr ""

#: ../../pyvista/doc/source/examples/01-filter/image_representations.rst:739
msgid ""
"For visualization, we color the points image (inner mesh) and show the cells"
" image (outer mesh) as a wireframe. We also plot the cell centers in red. "
"Note how the centers of the image of the cells correspond to the points of "
"the points image."
msgstr ""

